---

# Why This Works

The trick:

```python id="u1m5r8"
.lower()
```

makes:

```text id="q8x2p4"
uppercase and lowercase
```

share SAME hashmap key.

---

# Example

```python id="m3q7v1"
'A'.lower()
```

becomes:

```text id="y6p1r5"
'a'
```

So:

```text id="t9m4x2"
'a' and 'A'
```

both contribute to:

```python id="n5q8m3"
map_['a']
```

---

# Why set() is Important

Without:

```python id="u7m2p9"
set(word)
```

duplicates would incorrectly increase count.

---

# Example Without set()

```text id="k4r8m1"
"aaaA"
```

Map would become:

```text id="v2p5q7"
a = 4
```

But we only care whether:

```text id="m8x1r4"
both forms exist
```

NOT frequency.

So:

```python id="q3m7p2"
set()
```

removes duplicates first.

---

# Complexity Analysis

# Time Complexity

## set(word)

```text id="n6q2m8"
O(n)
```

## Traversal

```text id="y1p7r4"
O(n)
```

Total:

```text id="u5m9x3"
O(n)
```

---

# Space Complexity

Hashmap + set storage.

```text id="v4q8m1"
O(1)
```

Because max characters:

```text id="t2p6r9"
52 letters
```

---

# Key Insights

---

# 1. lower() Unifies Cases

```text id="x8m3q5"
A → a
B → b
```

Very important trick.

---

# 2. set() Removes Duplicate Noise

We only check:

```text id="p1r7m4"
existence
```

not frequency.

---

# 3. Count == 2 Means Special

Example:

```text id="m5x2q8"
a + A
```

both present.

---

# Edge Cases

---

# Case 1

## Input

```python id="v9m4r1"
word = "abc"
```

Map:

```text id="q7p2m6"
a=1,b=1,c=1
```

No value = 2.

Result:

```text id="u3x8q5"
0
```

---

# Case 2

## Input

```python id="k1m7p4"
word = "aA"
```

Map:

```text id="r8q2m5"
a=2
```

Result:

```text id="y4p9x1"
1
```

---

# Case 3

## Input

```python id="t6m3q8"
word = "aaAA"
```

After set:

```text id="v2p7m1"
['a','A']
```

Map:

```text id="x5r1q4"
a=2
```

Result:

```text id="m9p4x7"
1
```
